1. Cron expression formats
- Unix Vixie-style crontab: five fields: minute (0-59), hour (0-23), day of month (1-31), month (1-12), day of week (0-6 or 0/7 = Sunday). Typical line: "m h dom mon dow command".
- Some implementations accept a sixth field for user or year; Windows nnCron may use sixth for year.
- Quartz CronTrigger: six or seven fields: seconds (0-59), minutes (0-59), hours (0-23), day-of-month (1-31), month (1-12 or JAN-DEC), day-of-week (1-7 or SUN-SAT), optional year (empty or 1970-2099). Example minimal Quartz expression: "* * * * ? *".
- cron-parser (JS) supports six-field expressions where the first field is seconds (optional in some modes) and includes additional extensions (H, L with week variants, #, etc.).

2. Field semantics and allowed values
- Seconds: 0-59 (Quartz and cron-parser when using seconds)
- Minutes: 0-59
- Hours: 0-23
- Day of month: 1-31; special values: L (last day), LW/LW combinations, W (nearest weekday)
- Month: 1-12 or JAN-DEC; case-insensitive
- Day of week: Unix: 0-6 (0 or 7 = Sunday); Quartz: 1-7 or SUN-SAT; cron-parser allows 0-7 and SUN-SAT and 1L-7L for last-weekday
- Year: optional in Quartz; numeric range typically 1970-2099
- POSIX exception: when both day-of-month and day-of-week are restricted (not *), some Unix crons trigger if either field matches; Quartz requires using '?' in one of the two fields to avoid ambiguity.

3. Special characters and exact semantics
- * : all values for the field
- ? : no specific value (Quartz); in Unix often same as * or used to avoid ambiguity in day-of-month/day-of-week
- , : value list separator (e.g., MON,WED,FRI)
- - : inclusive range (e.g., 10-12)
- / : step values; can appear as "start/step" or "*/step" meaning every step units starting at start or 0
- L : last occurrence. Day-of-month: L = last day of month; Day-of-week: "6L" = last Friday of month; offsets allowed like L-3
- W : weekday nearest given day-of-month. E.g., 15W fires nearest weekday to 15th; special-case months boundaries: 1W on Saturday moves to Monday 3rd
- # : "nth" weekday of month; e.g., 6#3 = third Friday of month
- H (cron-parser extension): randomized deterministic hash-based value within field range; seedable via hashSeed option; supports ranges H(x-y) and steps H/step
- @macros (Unix): @yearly, @monthly, @weekly, @daily/@midnight, @hourly, @reboot; mapped to equivalent expressions except @reboot which triggers on daemon start only

4. Differences: Unix cron vs Quartz vs cron-parser
- Field count: Unix 5 fields (minute..dow), Quartz 6/7 (seconds included, year optional), cron-parser supports seconds and many Quartz-like extensions plus Jenkins-style H
- Day-of-month vs day-of-week resolution: Unix historically treats both fields such that if both are restricted, match occurs when either matches; Quartz enforces use of '?' in one field to disambiguate. cron-parser offers strict mode to reject expressions that set both DOM and DOW.
- Named months/days: Quartz and cron-parser accept JAN-DEC and SUN-SAT; UNIX crontab implementations differ but many support names.
- Time zones: many cron daemons run in system timezone; some accept CRON_TZ=TZNAME lines in crontabs to set timezone per crontab; cron-parser accepts tz option with IANA zone name and uses a timezone library (e.g., Luxon) to compute transitions and DST behavior.

5. Time zones and DST handling
- Use IANA tz database zone names (e.g., Europe/London, America/Los_Angeles). Do not use numeric offsets for persistent schedules where DST matters.
- IANA tzdb is distributed (e.g., tzdata2026a.tar.gz) and must be kept up-to-date when political boundary or DST rules change.
- During DST "spring forward" an hour may be skipped (some local times never occur); during "fall back" an hour is repeated. Schedulers must define behavior: prefer to interpret cron expressions in local time and either skip or repeat events according to wall-clock semantics.
- Best practice: schedule using local wall-clock semantics using IANA tz names and compute next-fire instants using a timezone-aware library (Luxon, ICU via Intl, or similar), ensuring correct handling of ambiguous or non-existent local instants by choosing well-documented resolution rules (e.g., prefer earlier/later or skip depending on desired semantics).

6. Parser behavior, options and iterator semantics (cron-parser)
- Primary API: CronExpressionParser.parse(expression: string, options?: CronExpressionOptions) returns a CronExpression/iterator object.
- Options (CronExpressionOptions):
  - currentDate: Date | string | number — the current date for iteration; defaults to now (UTC by default in cron-parser unless tz provided)
  - startDate: Date | string | number — iteration lower bound; if currentDate omitted and startDate provided, startDate becomes currentDate
  - endDate: Date | string | number — iteration upper bound; iteration throws when exceeding endDate
  - tz: string — IANA timezone identifier (e.g., 'Europe/London') used for computing next/prev in local time and converting to UTC instants
  - hashSeed: string — seed for deterministic H (jitter) values
  - strict: boolean — enable strict validation (rejects ambiguous DOM+DOW combos, requires full field count, rejects empty expression)
- Iterator methods and semantics:
  - next(): Date — returns next matching date (as Date object). Throws if next date would exceed endDate or iteration range
  - prev(): Date — returns previous matching date
  - take(n): Date[] — returns next n dates
  - iterator is iterable (for...of) and supports break
  - stringify()/toString(): returns canonical string representation of the parsed expression (with random H resolved when hashSeed used)
- Date range handling: if currentDate is outside startDate..endDate, the parser clamps currentDate to startDate when startDate provided; iteration enforces endDate bound and throws when exceeded
- Timezone handling: when tz is provided, parser computes matching local datetimes in tz and then converts to absolute instants (UTC) to return Date objects; DST transitions are handled by the underlying timezone library

7. Scheduling engine implementation notes (event queue, SIGHUP, @reboot)
- Efficient scheduler pattern: compute next-fire time for each job, insert into a priority/event queue (Franta–Maly event list recommended for efficiency) keyed by next-fire instant, sleep until head-of-queue time, wake and execute tasks, then compute and re-insert their next-fire times.
- On daemon start, scan crontabs, compute next times for each job, populate queue; on SIGHUP or file-change, recompute affected crontab entries and update queue atomically.
- CRON_TZ per-crontab: parse lines like CRON_TZ=Europe/London and apply that tz to subsequent expressions in that file; otherwise use daemon/system tz.
- @reboot: implement by queuing a one-time event at daemon startup only; do not re-run on cron daemon restarts unless design requires it.
- Job execution: fork/exec or spawn under job's configured user context where supported (system crontabs may include user field). Capture stdout/stderr and optionally email output to job owner.

SUPPLEMENTARY DETAILS (implementation specifications and configuration)

- Expression normalization: accept both numeric and named month/day tokens; convert to canonical numeric ranges internally for comparison.
- Field parsing: tokenize by whitespace for top-level fields; support optional seconds field when present (6th field vs 5-field mode). In strict mode require 6 fields.
- Range expansion: support single values, ranges (a-b), lists (a,b,c), steps (a/b or */b), and nested constructs like JAN-MAR/2.
- L/W/#: implement month-aware calculations: L for DOM => use lastDay = daysInMonth(year, month); L-3 => lastDay - 3; weekday nearest W => compute candidate day; if weekend, shift as per rules and month boundary checks.
- H hashing: compute deterministic hash(jobIdentifier + hashSeed) mapped into field range. When seed omitted, use randomized but repeatable per process life if desired.
- Time arithmetic: use timezone-aware library (recommended: Luxon or ICU-based) to compute local instants; handle ambiguous and nonexistent local times explicitly:
  - Non-existent (spring forward): choose strategy: 1) shift forward to next valid local time; 2) skip this local occurrence (no firing); document chosen policy. cron-parser uses timezone library semantics to compute next valid instant.
  - Ambiguous (fall back): choose earliest or latest mapping consistently; document and expose option if controllable.
- Validation: strict mode rejects expressions that set both DOM and DOW; default mode accepts and implements the historical behavior (match if either is satisfied) unless deploying Quartz-style semantics which requires '?' in one field.

